  "introduction": "Imagine you are reading a mystery novel. The author says, 'The door was locked.' Is that all? No! It implies no one can get in. Today, we learn to be detectives who find both the facts (locked door) and the hidden clues (no one can enter). This is the power of Reading Skills!",
  "theory": {
    "overview": "Reading Skills involve two main levels: Literal Comprehension (understanding what is explicitly written) and Inferential Comprehension (understanding what is implied). Students must learn to identify the Main Idea, use Context Clues for vocabulary, and analyze Tone.",
    "keyPoints": [
      "Literal comprehension focuses on facts directly stated in the text.",
      "Inferential comprehension requires reading between the lines.",
      "Context clues (synonyms, antonyms, examples) help decode unknown words.",
      "The Main Idea is usually found in the topic sentence."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "To master Reading Skills, students must move beyond passive reading. When reading a passage, ask: What is the author saying? (Literal). What do they mean? (Inferential). For example, if a text says 'The economy is in shambles,' the literal fact is that the economy is bad, but the inference is that people are suffering. Students should practice identifying the topic sentence to find the main idea and using surrounding words to guess meanings of difficult vocabulary."
  },
